= Energy Transfer and Trophic Efficiency

- Only 5–20% of assimilated energy passes between trophic levels; most energy is lost as heat or used for maintenance.
- *Ecological efficiency* or *food chain efficiency* is the percentage of energy transferred from one trophic level to the next.
- *Assimilation efficiency*: $assimilation\ efficiency = assimilated\ energy / ingested\ energy$; reflects food digestibility.
- *Net production efficiency*: $net\ production\ efficiency = growth\ and\ reproduction\ energy / assimilated\ energy$
- *Stoichiometry* (ecological stoichiometry): the study of the balance of multiple chemical elements in ecological interactions, especially the ratios of elements in food and consumer tissues and their effect on energy and nutrient transfer.
- Not all food components can be assimilated:
  #figure(
    image(images.at("22.13").path, width: 50%),
  )
- *Stoichiometry* affects assimilation efficiency; nutrient ratios in food vs. consumer tissues influence waste production.
- Nutrient requirements vary with biology and growth rates:
  #figure(
    image(images.at("22.14").path, width: 50%),
  )
- *Net production efficiency* is the percentage of assimilated energy used for growth and reproduction.

= Detritus Food Chains and Energy Movement

- *Detritus food chains* process dead plant material and indigestible excreta, especially important in terrestrial ecosystems. Energy moves more slowly through detritus chains than through herbivore chains.
- The proportion of NPP entering herbivore vs. detritus food chains varies among ecosystems.
- *Residence time*: $residence\ time = energy\ or\ biomass\ stored / net\ productivity$; indicates the average time energy or material remains in a trophic level or ecosystem compartment.
- Biomass accumulation ratios for primary producers:
